  <!-- PART 1: UNDERSTANDING THE SELF -->
  <!-- ═══════════════════════════════════════ -->

  <div id="uts-intro" style="margin:48px 0 16px;">
    <div style="font-size:.7rem;text-transform:uppercase;letter-spacing:3px;color:var(--accent1);font-weight:700;margin-bottom:8px;">Part I</div>
    <div style="font-family:'Playfair Display',serif;font-size:2.2rem;font-weight:900;margin-bottom:8px;">Understanding the Self</div>
    <div style="color:var(--text-muted);font-size:.9rem;max-width:600px;">This course asks one of the most ancient and important questions: <em>Who am I?</em> It explores the self through philosophy, sociology, psychology, and lived experience — essential for every Filipino college student.</div>
  </div>

  <!-- ─── CHAPTER 1 ─── -->
  <div class="chapter-block" id="ch1">
    <div class="chapter-header" data-num="01">
      <div>
        <div class="chapter-num">Chapter 1</div>
        <div class="chapter-title">The Philosophical Perspectives<br>on the Self</div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- SECTION: What is the Self? -->
    <div class="section">
      <button class="section-toggle open" onclick="toggleSection(this)">
        <h3><span class="section-icon icon-self">🔍</span>1.1 — What is the "Self"? Fundamental Questions</h3>
        <span class="chevron">▾</span>
      </button>
      <div class="section-body open">
        <p>The <span class="term">self</span> is one of the most debated concepts in human history. Philosophy, religion, science, and culture each offer different answers to the question: <em>"Who am I?"</em></p>

        <div class="callout callout-def">
          <div class="callout-label">Core Definition</div>
          <p>The <strong>self</strong> refers to the totality of an individual — the conscious, reflective being that experiences, thinks, feels, and acts. It is the subject of one's own experience.</p>
        </div>

        <h4>Why Study the Self?</h4>
        <ul class="styled-list">
          <li>Self-knowledge is the foundation of wisdom (Socratic tradition: "Know thyself")</li>
          <li>Understanding the self helps you make better decisions and build authentic relationships</li>
          <li>It reveals how society, culture, and biology shape who we are</li>
          <li>It is the starting point for ethics — knowing what you value and why</li>
          <li>In the Philippine context, understanding the self includes examining how being Filipino shapes identity</li>
        </ul>

        <h4>Three Core Questions About the Self</h4>
        <div class="theory-grid">
          <div class="theory-card">
            <h5>What AM I?</h5>
            <p>Is the self a soul, a brain, a bundle of experiences, or a social construction?</p>
            <span class="thinker">Metaphysical Question</span>
          </div>
          <div class="theory-card">
            <h5>Who AM I?</h5>
            <p>What makes you uniquely <em>you</em> across time — your memories, personality, values?</p>
            <span class="thinker">Identity Question</span>
          </div>
          <div class="theory-card">
            <h5>How should I LIVE?</h5>
            <p>What kind of person should I become? What gives my life meaning?</p>
            <span class="thinker">Ethical Question</span>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="takeaways">
          <div class="takeaways-label">Key Takeaways — Section 1.1</div>
          <ul>
            <li>The self is complex and studied across multiple disciplines</li>
            <li>"Know thyself" is the oldest imperative of self-study</li>
            <li>The self includes physical, mental, social, and spiritual dimensions</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- SECTION: Western Philosophy -->
    <div class="section">
      <button class="section-toggle open" onclick="toggleSection(this)">
        <h3><span class="section-icon icon-self">🏛️</span>1.2 — Western Philosophical Views on the Self</h3>
        <span class="chevron">▾</span>
      </button>
      <div class="section-body open">

        <div class="philosopher-quote">
          <p>"The unexamined life is not worth living."</p>
          <div class="quote-attr">— Socrates, Apology (399 BCE)</div>
        </div>

        <h4>Ancient Greek Perspectives</h4>

        <h5>Socrates (470–399 BCE)</h5>
        <p>Socrates believed the <span class="term">soul (psyche)</span> is the true self — not the body. The soul is immortal and the source of wisdom. His method — the <span class="term">Socratic dialogue</span> — used questioning to expose ignorance and arrive at self-knowledge.</p>
        <div class="callout callout-example">
          <div class="callout-label">Real-World Example</div>
          <p>When you challenge your own assumptions by asking "Why do I believe this?" — you are practicing Socratic self-examination.</p>
        </div>

        <h5>Plato (428–348 BCE)</h5>
        <p>Plato extended Socrates' view. In his dialogue <em>Phaedo</em>, he argues the soul is distinct from and superior to the body. The soul existed before birth and will survive death. True knowledge comes from the soul, not the senses.</p>
        <div class="callout callout-def">
          <div class="callout-label">Platonic Dualism</div>
          <p>The soul/body divide. The body is a prison for the immortal soul. The soul strives toward the <em>Forms</em> — eternal, perfect realities like Beauty, Justice, and Goodness.</p>
        </div>
        <p>Plato also identified three parts of the soul in the <em>Republic</em>:</p>
        <ul class="styled-list">
          <li><strong>Reason (Logos)</strong> — the rational part, should govern the self</li>
          <li><strong>Spirit (Thumos)</strong> — the emotional/competitive part</li>
          <li><strong>Appetite (Epithumia)</strong> — desires, pleasures, and basic drives</li>
        </ul>

        <h5>Aristotle (384–322 BCE)</h5>
        <p>Aristotle rejected Plato's dualism. For him, the soul (<span class="term">psyche</span>) is the <em>form</em> of the body — inseparable from it. You cannot have a soul without a body.</p>
        <div class="callout callout-def">
          <div class="callout-label">Aristotle's Hylomorphism</div>
          <p>Matter (body) + Form (soul) = Living being. The soul is what makes a living body alive. There is no disembodied soul floating apart from the body.</p>
        </div>
        <p>Aristotle's key concept for the self: <span class="term">eudaimonia</span> (flourishing/happiness), achieved through virtuous activity in accordance with reason. The self is realized through action and community.</p>

        <h4>Modern Western Views</h4>

        <h5>René Descartes (1596–1650) — Cogito, ergo sum</h5>
        <p>Descartes is the father of modern philosophy. His method: <span class="term">radical doubt</span> — doubt everything until you find something indubitable. His conclusion: <em>"I think, therefore I am."</em></p>
        <div class="callout callout-def">
          <div class="callout-label">Cartesian Dualism</div>
          <p>Mind (res cogitans — thinking substance) and Body (res extensa — extended substance) are completely separate. The self is essentially the <em>mind</em>, a non-physical thinking thing inhabiting the body.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="callout callout-warning">
          <div class="callout-label">Common Mistake</div>
          <p>Students often confuse Plato and Descartes. Both are dualists, but Plato sees the soul as metaphysically primary (seeking the Forms), while Descartes grounds the self in the certainty of <em>thought itself</em>.</p>
        </div>

        <h5>John Locke (1632–1704) — Personal Identity through Memory</h5>
        <p>Locke argued that personal identity is constituted by <span class="term">consciousness and memory</span>, not by substance. You are the same person over time because you remember your past experiences.</p>
        <div class="callout callout-example">
          <div class="callout-label">Example</div>
          <p>If you cannot remember being a child, are you the same person? Locke would say continuity of memory = continuity of self.</p>
        </div>

        <h5>David Hume (1711–1776) — No Permanent Self</h5>
        <p>Hume challenged the notion of a unified self. When he introspected, he found only a <em>bundle of perceptions</em> — sensations, thoughts, emotions — but no underlying "self" that has them.</p>
        <div class="callout callout-def">
          <div class="callout-label">Bundle Theory</div>
          <p>The self is not a substance but a collection of ever-changing perceptions. There is no stable "I" behind your experiences — only the experiences themselves.</p>
        </div>
        <p>This is strikingly similar to Buddhist ideas of <span class="term">anattā</span> (no-self).</p>

        <h5>Immanuel Kant (1724–1804) — The Transcendental Self</h5>
        <p>Kant synthesized rationalism and empiricism. He distinguished between:</p>
        <ul class="styled-list">
          <li><span class="term">Empirical self</span> — the self as known through experience, in time and space</li>
          <li><span class="term">Transcendental self</span> (the "I think") — the condition that makes experience possible; the unity behind all our thoughts</li>
        </ul>
        <p>For Kant, the self is both knower and moral agent. As a rational being, you are subject to the <em>Categorical Imperative</em> (covered in Ethics section).</p>

        <h5>Jean-Paul Sartre (1905–1980) — Existence Precedes Essence</h5>
        <p>Sartre's existentialism: there is no pre-given human nature. You are "condemned to be free" and must create yourself through choices. The self is a project, not a fixed thing.</p>
        <div class="callout callout-def">
          <div class="callout-label">Existentialist Self</div>
          <p>"Existence precedes essence" — You exist first, then define yourself through action. There is no God-given essence that determines who you must be.</p>
        </div>

        <h4>Eastern Philosophical Views</h4>

        <h5>Hindu Perspective — Atman and Brahman</h5>
        <p>In Hinduism, the true self is <span class="term">Atman</span> — the eternal, divine soul. Atman is ultimately identical with <span class="term">Brahman</span>, the universal consciousness. Self-realization is recognizing this identity.</p>

        <h5>Buddhist Perspective — Anattā (No-Self)</h5>
        <p>Buddhism radically denies a permanent self. The "self" is an illusion composed of five aggregates (<span class="term">skandhas</span>):</p>
        <ul class="styled-list">
          <li>Form (rupa) — the physical body</li>
          <li>Sensation (vedana) — feelings</li>
          <li>Perception (samjna) — recognition</li>
          <li>Mental formations (samskara) — intentions, habits</li>
          <li>Consciousness (vijnana) — awareness</li>
        </ul>
        <p>Clinging to a permanent self is the root of suffering (dukkha).</p>

        <h5>Confucian Perspective — Relational Self</h5>
        <p>In Confucianism, the self is defined through relationships and social roles — as child, parent, sibling, friend, citizen. The self is not isolated but fundamentally relational.</p>

        <table class="compare-table">
          <thead><tr><th>Philosopher</th><th>Nature of Self</th><th>Key Concept</th></tr></thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr><td>Socrates</td><td>Soul (psyche)</td><td>Know thyself</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Plato</td><td>Immaterial soul, tripartite</td><td>Soul superior to body</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Aristotle</td><td>Soul as form of body</td><td>Eudaimonia through virtue</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Descartes</td><td>Thinking substance (mind)</td><td>Cogito, ergo sum</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Locke</td><td>Consciousness + memory</td><td>Personal identity = memory</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Hume</td><td>Bundle of perceptions</td><td>No permanent self</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Kant</td><td>Transcendental unity</td><td>Empirical + transcendental self</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Sartre</td><td>Self-created project</td><td>Existence precedes essence</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Buddhism</td><td>No-self (anattā)</td><td>Illusion of self</td></tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>

        <div class="takeaways">
          <div class="takeaways-label">Key Takeaways — Section 1.2</div>
          <ul>
            <li>Western philosophy largely debated whether the self is substance (soul/mind) or process (bundle)</li>
            <li>Descartes' "I think therefore I am" is the cornerstone of modern selfhood</li>
            <li>Eastern philosophies challenge the very existence of a permanent self</li>
            <li>Sartre's existentialism places radical responsibility for self-creation on the individual</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- Practice Q ch1 -->
    <div class="pq-block">
      <div class="pq-question" onclick="toggleAnswer(this)">
        <span class="pq-num">Q1</span>
        <span>Explain what Descartes meant by "Cogito, ergo sum" and how it relates to the nature of the self.</span>
      </div>
      <div class="pq-answer">
        <div class="pq-answer-label">Model Answer</div>
        Descartes used radical doubt to strip away all uncertain beliefs. He found he could not doubt that he was doubting — and doubting is a form of thinking. Therefore, the act of thinking proves that he exists as a thinking thing. This establishes the self as essentially a mind (res cogitans), separate from the body (res extensa). The self is not proven by the senses or the body, but by the very act of conscious thought.
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="pq-block">
      <div class="pq-question" onclick="toggleAnswer(this)">
        <span class="pq-num">Q2</span>
        <span>Compare Hume's "bundle theory" with the Buddhist concept of anattā.</span>
      </div>
      <div class="pq-answer">
        <div class="pq-answer-label">Model Answer</div>
        Both Hume and Buddhism deny a permanent, unified self. Hume, through empirical introspection, found only a "bundle of perceptions" — fleeting sensations and thoughts — with no underlying substance. Buddhism similarly teaches anattā (no-self), arguing the self is a temporary collection of five aggregates (skandhas). The key difference: Hume arrives at this through Western empiricist philosophy, while Buddhism frames it within a soteriological (liberation-focused) context — recognizing no-self leads to the end of suffering.
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- ─── CHAPTER 2 ─── -->
  <div class="chapter-block" id="ch2">
    <div class="chapter-header" data-num="02">
      <div>
        <div class="chapter-num">Chapter 2</div>
        <div class="chapter-title">The Sociological Self:<br>Society, Culture & Identity</div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="section">
      <button class="section-toggle open" onclick="toggleSection(this)">
        <h3><span class="section-icon icon-self">👥</span>2.1 — How Society Shapes the Self</h3>
        <span class="chevron">▾</span>
      </button>
      <div class="section-body open">
        <p>While philosophy asks "What is the self?", sociology asks: "How is the self <em>made</em> through social interaction?" The sociological tradition argues the self is not pre-given but constructed through society, culture, language, and relationships.</p>

        <h4>George Herbert Mead — The Social Self</h4>
        <div class="callout callout-def">
          <div class="callout-label">Mead's Theory (Symbolic Interactionism)</div>
          <p>The self emerges through social interaction using symbols (especially language). We become ourselves by taking the perspective of others.</p>
        </div>
        <p>Mead distinguished two aspects of the self:</p>
        <ul class="styled-list">
          <li><span class="term">The "I"</span> — the spontaneous, creative, impulsive self; the subject</li>
          <li><span class="term">The "Me"</span> — the socialized self; the self as seen by others; the internalized social norms</li>
        </ul>
        <p>The self develops in three stages:</p>
        <ol class="styled-list">
          <li><strong>Preparatory Stage</strong> — Children imitate others without understanding meaning</li>
          <li><strong>Play Stage</strong> — Children play roles (doctor, parent); take the perspective of one other</li>
          <li><strong>Game Stage</strong> — Children understand rules and take the perspective of the "generalized other" (society as a whole)</li>
        </ol>
        <div class="callout callout-example">
          <div class="callout-label">Philippine Context</div>
          <p>A Filipino child learns to address elders as "po" and "opo" — internalizing respect (galang) as part of the socialized "Me." The "I" might sometimes resist, but the "Me" enforces social expectations.</p>
        </div>

        <h4>Charles Cooley — The Looking Glass Self</h4>
        <div class="callout callout-def">
          <div class="callout-label">Looking Glass Self</div>
          <p>Our self-concept is formed by imagining how we appear to others, imagining their judgment of us, and developing our self-concept accordingly. Other people are our "social mirror."</p>
        </div>
        <p>Three elements of the looking glass self:</p>
        <ul class="styled-list">
          <li>We imagine how we appear to another person</li>
          <li>We imagine their judgment of that appearance</li>
          <li>We develop our self through that imagined judgment (pride or shame)</li>
        </ul>
        <div class="callout callout-example">
          <div class="callout-label">Example</div>
          <p>If classmates consistently treat you as smart and capable, you begin to see yourself as intelligent — even if you initially doubted yourself. Social feedback shapes self-image.</p>
        </div>

        <h4>Erving Goffman — Dramaturgical Model</h4>
        <p>Goffman compared social life to a theatrical performance. The self is not a fixed entity but a performance managed to create desired impressions.</p>
        <ul class="styled-list">
          <li><span class="term">Front stage</span> — where we perform for others; manage impressions; follow social scripts</li>
          <li><span class="term">Back stage</span> — where we relax, step out of roles, and are "ourselves"</li>
          <li><span class="term">Impression management</span> — active control of how we present ourselves</li>
        </ul>
        <div class="callout callout-example">
          <div class="callout-label">Modern Example</div>
          <p>Your curated Instagram profile is the "front stage." Your private life — including how you behave at home — is the "back stage." The self differs across contexts.</p>
        </div>

        <h4>Socialization: How the Self is Formed</h4>
        <p><span class="term">Socialization</span> is the lifelong process by which individuals learn the norms, values, behaviors, and social skills of their society.</p>
        <h5>Primary Socialization</h5>
        <p>Occurs in childhood. The primary agents are the <strong>family</strong>. Core values, language, and identity are first learned here. In the Philippines, this includes learning Filipino values like <em>utang na loob</em>, <em>hiya</em>, and <em>pakikisama</em>.</p>
        <h5>Secondary Socialization</h5>
        <p>Occurs throughout life through schools, peers, media, religion, and workplace. These agents reinforce or modify the self formed in primary socialization.</p>

        <h4>Key Filipino Values and the Self</h4>
        <table class="compare-table">
          <thead><tr><th>Filipino Value</th><th>Meaning</th><th>Effect on Self</th></tr></thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr><td>Hiya (Shame)</td><td>Sensitivity to social judgment; avoidance of disgrace</td><td>Self regulated by fear of public embarrassment</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Utang na Loob</td><td>Debt of gratitude; reciprocity</td><td>Self defined by obligations to others</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Pakikisama</td><td>Group harmony; going along with the group</td><td>Self subordinated to communal welfare</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Bayanihan</td><td>Communal unity and cooperation</td><td>Self fulfillment through collective effort</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Kapwa</td><td>Shared identity; unity of self and other</td><td>Self understood as inherently relational</td></tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>

        <div class="callout callout-def">
          <div class="callout-label">Dr. Virgilio Enriquez — Kapwa</div>
          <p><strong>Kapwa</strong> (shared identity/shared being) is the core of Filipino personhood. Unlike Western individualism, the Filipino self is inherently social — "I" cannot exist without "We." This is the foundation of Sikolohiyang Pilipino (Filipino Psychology).</p>
        </div>

        <div class="takeaways">
          <div class="takeaways-label">Key Takeaways — Section 2.1</div>
          <ul>
            <li>The self is socially constructed through interaction, not born fully formed</li>
            <li>Mead: the self has an "I" (spontaneous) and "Me" (social) dimension</li>
            <li>Cooley: we see ourselves through others' eyes (looking glass self)</li>
            <li>Goffman: we perform different selves in different social contexts</li>
            <li>Filipino selfhood is relational — rooted in kapwa, hiya, and utang na loob</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="pq-block">
      <div class="pq-question" onclick="toggleAnswer(this)">
        <span class="pq-num">Q3</span>
        <span>How does Cooley's "looking glass self" apply to social media use among Filipino youth?</span>
      </div>
      <div class="pq-answer">
        <div class="pq-answer-label">Model Answer</div>
        Cooley's looking glass self involves imagining how others see us, imagining their judgment, and developing our self-concept accordingly. On social media (e.g., Facebook, TikTok), Filipino youth post content and monitor likes, comments, and reactions. Positive reactions (likes, praise) reinforce positive self-concept, while negative comments or low engagement can trigger shame (hiya) and lowered self-esteem. Social media amplifies the looking glass effect — the "social mirror" is now public, persistent, and quantified. This creates heightened image consciousness and vulnerability to others' judgments.
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- ─── CHAPTER 3 ─── -->
  <div class="chapter-block" id="ch3">
    <div class="chapter-header" data-num="03">
      <div>
        <div class="chapter-num">Chapter 3</div>
        <div class="chapter-title">The Psychological Self:<br>Development, Identity & Personality</div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="section">
      <button class="section-toggle open" onclick="toggleSection(this)">
        <h3><span class="section-icon icon-self">🧠</span>3.1 — Psychological Theories of the Self</h3>
        <span class="chevron">▾</span>
      </button>
      <div class="section-body open">

        <h4>Sigmund Freud — The Psychoanalytic Self</h4>
        <p>Freud proposed that the self (psyche) is structured into three systems:</p>
        <div class="theory-grid">
          <div class="theory-card">
            <h5>Id</h5>
            <p>Unconscious reservoir of primal drives and desires (Eros/Thanatos). Operates on the <em>pleasure principle</em> — immediate gratification.</p>
            <span class="thinker">Freud</span>
          </div>
          <div class="theory-card">
            <h5>Ego</h5>
            <p>The conscious, rational self. Operates on the <em>reality principle</em> — balances id desires with external constraints.</p>
            <span class="thinker">Freud</span>
          </div>
          <div class="theory-card">
            <h5>Superego</h5>
            <p>Internalized moral standards (conscience). The critical voice of parents and society. Creates guilt when violated.</p>
            <span class="thinker">Freud</span>
          </div>
        </div>
        <p>Freud also identified <span class="term">defense mechanisms</span> — unconscious strategies the ego uses to protect the self from anxiety:</p>
        <ul class="styled-list">
          <li><strong>Repression</strong> — pushing painful memories into the unconscious</li>
          <li><strong>Denial</strong> — refusing to accept reality</li>
          <li><strong>Projection</strong> — attributing your own unacceptable feelings to others</li>
          <li><strong>Rationalization</strong> — creating logical justifications for irrational behavior</li>
          <li><strong>Sublimation</strong> — channeling unacceptable impulses into socially acceptable outlets (e.g., art)</li>
          <li><strong>Displacement</strong> — redirecting feelings toward a safer target</li>
        </ul>

        <h4>Carl Jung — The Collective Unconscious and Archetypes</h4>
        <p>Jung extended Freud's unconscious concept. He proposed:</p>
        <ul class="styled-list">
          <li><span class="term">Personal unconscious</span> — individual repressed content (like Freud's unconscious)</li>
          <li><span class="term">Collective unconscious</span> — shared layer of the unconscious containing universal symbols inherited from humanity</li>
          <li><span class="term">Archetypes</span> — universal symbolic patterns (The Hero, The Shadow, The Anima/Animus, The Self)</li>
        </ul>
        <div class="callout callout-def">
          <div class="callout-label">The Shadow</div>
          <p>The "dark side" of the personality — the parts of ourselves we deny or repress. Jung believed integrating the Shadow is essential for psychological wholeness (individuation).</p>
        </div>

        <h4>Erik Erikson — Psychosocial Development</h4>
        <p>Erikson proposed eight stages of human development, each marked by a psychosocial crisis whose resolution shapes identity:</p>
        <table class="compare-table">
          <thead><tr><th>Stage</th><th>Age</th><th>Crisis</th><th>Positive Resolution</th></tr></thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr><td>1. Infancy</td><td>0–1</td><td>Trust vs. Mistrust</td><td>Hope</td></tr>
            <tr><td>2. Early Childhood</td><td>1–3</td><td>Autonomy vs. Shame</td><td>Will</td></tr>
            <tr><td>3. Play Age</td><td>3–6</td><td>Initiative vs. Guilt</td><td>Purpose</td></tr>
            <tr><td>4. School Age</td><td>6–12</td><td>Industry vs. Inferiority</td><td>Competence</td></tr>
            <tr><td>5. Adolescence</td><td>12–18</td><td>Identity vs. Role Confusion</td><td>Fidelity</td></tr>
            <tr><td>6. Young Adulthood</td><td>18–40</td><td>Intimacy vs. Isolation</td><td>Love</td></tr>
            <tr><td>7. Middle Adulthood</td><td>40–65</td><td>Generativity vs. Stagnation</td><td>Care</td></tr>
            <tr><td>8. Late Adulthood</td><td>65+</td><td>Ego Integrity vs. Despair</td><td>Wisdom</td></tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
        <div class="callout callout-example">
          <div class="callout-label">Stage 5 — Most Relevant to College Students</div>
          <p>Identity vs. Role Confusion (adolescence/early adulthood): The key task is forming a coherent identity. College students exploring careers, relationships, and values are navigating this stage. Successful resolution yields a stable sense of self; failure results in confusion about roles and direction.</p>
        </div>

        <h4>Abraham Maslow — Hierarchy of Needs</h4>
        <p>Maslow's pyramid of human motivation shows that the self strives for increasingly higher levels of fulfillment:</p>
        <ul class="styled-list">
          <li><strong>Level 1 — Physiological</strong>: Food, water, shelter, sleep</li>
          <li><strong>Level 2 — Safety</strong>: Security, stability, freedom from fear</li>
          <li><strong>Level 3 — Love/Belonging</strong>: Friendship, intimacy, family, community</li>
          <li><strong>Level 4 — Esteem</strong>: Achievement, respect, recognition</li>
          <li><strong>Level 5 — Self-Actualization</strong>: Realizing one's full potential; creativity, purpose</li>
        </ul>
        <div class="callout callout-def">
          <div class="callout-label">Self-Actualization</div>
          <p>The highest level — becoming the best version of yourself. Maslow described self-actualized people as spontaneous, creative, reality-centered, autonomous, and having peak experiences.</p>
        </div>

        <h4>Carl Rogers — The Humanistic Self (Person-Centered)</h4>
        <p>Rogers believed humans have an innate drive toward growth (<span class="term">actualizing tendency</span>). Psychological health requires:</p>
        <ul class="styled-list">
          <li><span class="term">Unconditional positive regard</span> — being loved/accepted without conditions</li>
          <li><span class="term">Empathy</span> — being genuinely understood by others</li>
          <li><span class="term">Congruence</span> — alignment between the <em>ideal self</em> (who you want to be) and the <em>real self</em> (who you are)</li>
        </ul>
        <p>When the gap between real self and ideal self is too large, <span class="term">incongruence</span> leads to anxiety and psychological distress.</p>

        <h4>James Marcia — Identity Statuses</h4>
        <p>Building on Erikson, Marcia identified four identity statuses based on exploration and commitment:</p>
        <div class="theory-grid">
          <div class="theory-card">
            <h5>Identity Diffusion</h5>
            <p>No exploration, no commitment. Drifting without goals or values.</p>
            <span class="thinker">Marcia</span>
          </div>
          <div class="theory-card">
            <h5>Identity Foreclosure</h5>
            <p>Commitment without exploration — accepting others' choices (e.g., family-chosen career).</p>
            <span class="thinker">Marcia</span>
          </div>
          <div class="theory-card">
            <h5>Identity Moratorium</h5>
            <p>Exploring alternatives actively, but no commitment yet — in crisis.</p>
            <span class="thinker">Marcia</span>
          </div>
          <div class="theory-card">
            <h5>Identity Achievement</h5>
            <p>Has explored and committed to a self-chosen identity. Most mature status.</p>
            <span class="thinker">Marcia</span>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="takeaways">
          <div class="takeaways-label">Key Takeaways — Section 3.1</div>
          <ul>
            <li>Freud's id/ego/superego explains internal conflict and defense mechanisms</li>
            <li>Erikson's Stage 5 (Identity vs. Role Confusion) is the critical adolescent task</li>
            <li>Maslow's hierarchy culminates in self-actualization</li>
            <li>Rogers emphasizes congruence between real self and ideal self for mental health</li>
            <li>Marcia's identity achievement (explore + commit) is the healthiest outcome</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="pq-block">
      <div class="pq-question" onclick="toggleAnswer(this)">
        <span class="pq-num">Q4</span>
        <span>A college student is pressured by parents to take Medicine, but dreams of becoming an artist. Using Rogers' theory, analyze this situation.</span>
      </div>
      <div class="pq-answer">
        <div class="pq-answer-label">Model Answer</div>
        Rogers would diagnose this as <em>incongruence</em> — a gap between the real self (aspiring artist) and the ideal self being imposed externally (doctor to satisfy parents). The student is experiencing conditional positive regard (love and approval contingent on following parents' wishes), which damages psychological health. Rogers would advocate for unconditional positive regard — accepting the student as an artist — and helping the student develop congruence by aligning their choices with their genuine self. Continued incongruence leads to anxiety, low self-worth, and potentially abandoning the actualizing tendency.
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- ─── CHAPTER 4 ─── -->
  <div class="chapter-block" id="ch4">
    <div class="chapter-header" data-num="04">
      <div>
        <div class="chapter-num">Chapter 4</div>
        <div class="chapter-title">The Physical Self:<br>Body, Health & Self-Concept</div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="section">
      <button class="section-toggle open" onclick="toggleSection(this)">
        <h3><span class="section-icon icon-blue">💪</span>4.1 — The Body as the Self</h3>
        <span class="chevron">▾</span>
      </button>
      <div class="section-body open">
        <p>The body is not merely a vessel for the mind — it is an integral dimension of the self. How we experience, perceive, and present our bodies profoundly shapes identity.</p>

        <h4>Body Image</h4>
        <div class="callout callout-def">
          <div class="callout-label">Definition</div>
          <p><strong>Body image</strong> is the subjective perception of one's own body — how you think, feel, and act in relation to your physical appearance. It includes:</p>
        </div>
        <ul class="styled-list">
          <li><strong>Perceptual</strong> — how you perceive your body's size, shape, weight</li>
          <li><strong>Affective</strong> — feelings about your body (satisfaction/dissatisfaction)</li>
          <li><strong>Cognitive</strong> — thoughts and beliefs about your body</li>
          <li><strong>Behavioral</strong> — actions related to body image (dieting, exercise, avoidance)</li>
        </ul>

        <h4>Factors Affecting Body Image</h4>
        <ul class="styled-list">
          <li><strong>Media and social media</strong> — unrealistic standards of beauty</li>
          <li><strong>Peers and family</strong> — comments, comparisons, teasing</li>
          <li><strong>Culture</strong> — Filipino colonial mentality (preference for light skin, e.g., "maputi")</li>
          <li><strong>Gender norms</strong> — different beauty standards for men and women</li>
          <li><strong>Disability and illness</strong> — changed body image post-illness</li>
        </ul>

        <div class="callout callout-warning">
          <div class="callout-label">Philippine Context — Colonial Mentality</div>
          <p>Many Filipinos internalize colonial beauty standards — preferring lighter skin, sharper features, and Western looks. This is linked to centuries of Spanish and American colonization and affects self-esteem and body image.</p>
        </div>

        <h4>Maurice Merleau-Ponty — Phenomenology of the Body</h4>
        <p>Merleau-Ponty challenged Cartesian dualism. He argued the body is not an object we "have" but the very medium through which we experience the world — the <span class="term">lived body</span>.</p>
        <div class="callout callout-def">
          <div class="callout-label">Lived Body</div>
          <p>We do not simply "have" a body; we "are" our body. The body is the subject of experience, not merely an object. Our bodily skills (walking, speaking, playing) shape consciousness.</p>
        </div>

        <h4>Self-Care and Well-being</h4>
        <p>A healthy relationship with one's physical self involves:</p>
        <ul class="styled-list">
          <li>Physical health practices (nutrition, exercise, sleep)</li>
          <li>Positive body acceptance — rejecting toxic beauty standards</li>
          <li>Mental health awareness — recognizing body dysmorphia, eating disorders</li>
          <li>Holistic well-being — integration of physical, mental, social, and spiritual health</li>
        </ul>

        <div class="callout callout-tip">
          <div class="callout-label">Study Tip</div>
          <p>Connect Merleau-Ponty's "lived body" to Aristotle's hylomorphism — both reject sharp mind-body dualism. In exams, you may be asked to compare these views.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="takeaways">
          <div class="takeaways-label">Key Takeaways — Section 4.1</div>
          <ul>
            <li>Body image is a multi-dimensional perception of one's physical self</li>
            <li>Cultural and media standards profoundly shape body image</li>
            <li>Filipino colonial mentality affects beauty standards and self-esteem</li>
            <li>Merleau-Ponty: we don't "have" a body — we "are" our body (lived body)</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- ─── CHAPTER 5 ─── -->
  <div class="chapter-block" id="ch5">
    <div class="chapter-header" data-num="05">
      <div>
        <div class="chapter-num">Chapter 5</div>
        <div class="chapter-title">The Sexual & Gendered Self</div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="section">
      <button class="section-toggle open" onclick="toggleSection(this)">
        <h3><span class="section-icon icon-self">🏳️</span>5.1 — Sex, Gender & Identity</h3>
        <span class="chevron">▾</span>
      </button>
      <div class="section-body open">
        <h4>Key Distinctions</h4>
        <table class="compare-table">
          <thead><tr><th>Concept</th><th>Definition</th><th>Example</th></tr></thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr><td>Biological Sex</td><td>Anatomical/physiological characteristics (chromosomes, hormones, anatomy)</td><td>Male, Female, Intersex</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Gender Identity</td><td>Internal sense of being a man, woman, non-binary, etc.</td><td>Can align or differ from biological sex</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Gender Expression</td><td>External presentation — clothing, behavior, mannerisms</td><td>Masculine, Feminine, Androgynous</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Sexual Orientation</td><td>Emotional/romantic/sexual attraction patterns</td><td>Heterosexual, Gay, Bisexual, Asexual</td></tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>

        <h4>Judith Butler — Gender as Performance</h4>
        <div class="callout callout-def">
          <div class="callout-label">Butler's Performativity</div>
          <p>Gender is not a fixed essence but a <em>performance</em> — a repeated set of acts, gestures, and behaviors that create the appearance of a stable gender identity. There is no "original" gender beneath the performance.</p>
        </div>
        <p>This challenges the idea that biological sex naturally determines gender behavior. Society enforces gender norms through institutions, language, and repetition.</p>

        <h4>Gender in Philippine Culture</h4>
        <ul class="styled-list">
          <li>Pre-colonial Philippines had diverse gender roles — babaylans (spirit mediums) could be male, female, or gender-variant</li>
          <li>Spanish colonization imposed binary gender norms tied to Catholicism</li>
          <li>Contemporary Philippines has visible LGBTQIA+ communities but faces discrimination</li>
          <li>Legal context: no anti-discrimination law at national level (as of knowledge cutoff); SOGIE Equality Bill long-pending</li>
          <li>Filipino cultural term: <span class="term">bakla</span> — complex identity not reducible to Western "gay"</li>
        </ul>

        <h4>Gender Socialization</h4>
        <p>From birth, children are socialized into gender roles through toys, clothing, language, media, school, and religious teachings. This process shapes the gendered self deeply and often unconsciously.</p>

        <div class="callout callout-tip">
          <div class="callout-label">Key Insight</div>
          <p>The feminist claim "The personal is political" means that gender inequality is not just a private matter but a systemic social issue embedded in laws, culture, and power structures.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="takeaways">
          <div class="takeaways-label">Key Takeaways — Section 5.1</div>
          <ul>
            <li>Sex (biological) ≠ Gender (social/psychological) ≠ Sexual orientation</li>
            <li>Butler: gender is performed, not innate</li>
            <li>Filipino gender history includes pre-colonial gender diversity disrupted by colonization</li>
            <li>Gender socialization begins at birth and shapes the self throughout life</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- ─── CHAPTER 6 ─── -->
  <div class="chapter-block" id="ch6">
    <div class="chapter-header" data-num="06">
      <div>
        <div class="chapter-num">Chapter 6</div>
        <div class="chapter-title">The Spiritual Self</div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="section">
      <button class="section-toggle open" onclick="toggleSection(this)">
        <h3><span class="section-icon icon-green">✨</span>6.1 — Spirituality, Religion & the Self</h3>
        <span class="chevron">▾</span>
      </button>
      <div class="section-body open">
        <h4>Defining the Spiritual Self</h4>
        <div class="callout callout-def">
          <div class="callout-label">Spirituality vs. Religion</div>
          <p><strong>Religion</strong> — organized system of beliefs, practices, and community centered on the sacred. <strong>Spirituality</strong> — personal relationship with meaning, transcendence, and purpose; may or may not be connected to organized religion.</p>
        </div>

        <h4>William James — The Varieties of Religious Experience</h4>
        <p>James identified core features of religious/spiritual experience: ineffability (beyond words), noetic quality (reveals deep truths), transience, and passivity. He argued these experiences are real and have genuine effects on the self.</p>

        <h4>Viktor Frankl — Meaning and the Self</h4>
        <p>Frankl, a Holocaust survivor, developed <span class="term">logotherapy</span> — the view that the primary human drive is not pleasure (Freud) or power (Adler) but <em>meaning</em>.</p>
        <div class="callout callout-example">
          <div class="callout-label">Frankl's Key Insight</div>
          <p>"He who has a why to live for can bear almost any how." Even in extreme suffering, the self can find meaning — and this is the ultimate human freedom.</p>
        </div>

        <h4>The Spiritual Self in the Filipino Context</h4>
        <ul class="styled-list">
          <li>Philippines is approximately 86% Catholic — religion deeply shapes Filipino identity</li>
          <li>Concepts like <em>bahala na</em> (leave it to God/fate) reflect a spiritually oriented outlook</li>
          <li>Indigenous spiritual practices (animism, ancestor veneration) still present in some communities</li>
          <li>The Nazareno, Sinulog, and Ati-Atihan festivals illustrate folk Catholicism's role in self and community</li>
        </ul>

        <h4>Functions of the Spiritual Self</h4>
        <ul class="styled-list">
          <li>Provides meaning and purpose in life</li>
          <li>Offers comfort in suffering and death</li>
          <li>Creates moral framework (what is right and wrong)</li>
          <li>Connects the individual to something larger — community, cosmos, or God</li>
          <li>Fosters resilience (Filipino resilience is often spiritually grounded)</li>
        </ul>

        <div class="takeaways">
          <div class="takeaways-label">Key Takeaways — Section 6.1</div>
          <ul>
            <li>Spirituality (personal) and religion (organized) both shape the self</li>
            <li>Frankl: meaning-seeking is the core human drive; even suffering can have meaning</li>
            <li>Filipino spiritual identity is shaped by Catholicism, indigenous beliefs, and folk practices</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- ─── CHAPTER 7 ─── -->
  <div class="chapter-block" id="ch7">
    <div class="chapter-header" data-num="07">
      <div>
        <div class="chapter-num">Chapter 7</div>
        <div class="chapter-title">The Political & Economic Self</div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="section">
      <button class="section-toggle open" onclick="toggleSection(this)">
        <h3><span class="section-icon icon-self">🏛️</span>7.1 — Political Identity and Economic Conditions</h3>
        <span class="chevron">▾</span>
      </button>
      <div class="section-body open">
        <h4>The Political Self</h4>
        <p>Political identity refers to how citizens understand themselves in relation to the state, political systems, rights, and civic duties.</p>
        <ul class="styled-list">
          <li><span class="term">Citizenship</span> — legal membership in a political community with rights and responsibilities</li>
          <li><span class="term">Political socialization</span> — how family, school, media, and peers shape political beliefs</li>
          <li><span class="term">Active citizenship</span> — participating in governance, elections, and social movements</li>
        </ul>
        <div class="callout callout-example">
          <div class="callout-label">Philippine Context</div>
          <p>The 1986 EDSA People Power Revolution is a landmark in Filipino political self-consciousness — citizens collectively reclaimed their identity as a democratic people against authoritarianism.</p>
        </div>

        <h4>The Economic Self</h4>
        <p>Economic conditions deeply shape self-concept, opportunities, and life choices.</p>
        <ul class="styled-list">
          <li>Class position influences access to education, healthcare, and upward mobility</li>
          <li>Labor and work give meaning and structure to the self</li>
          <li>Marx: alienated labor — workers estranged from the product of their labor and from their own humanity</li>
          <li>OFW identity — millions of Filipinos define their economic self through overseas labor, reshaping family and national identity</li>
        </ul>

        <h4>Class, Privilege & Self-Awareness</h4>
        <p>Understanding one's class position, privileges, and disadvantages is part of critical self-knowledge. Intersectionality — how class intersects with gender, race, and religion — shapes the self in complex ways.</p>

        <div class="takeaways">
          <div class="takeaways-label">Key Takeaways — Section 7.1</div>
          <ul>
            <li>Political identity is shaped by citizenship, rights, and civic participation</li>
            <li>Economic conditions — class, work, labor — profoundly shape the self</li>
            <li>Filipino political self is marked by colonial history and democratic aspirations</li>
            <li>OFW identity is a uniquely Filipino economic and social phenomenon</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- ─── CHAPTER 8 ─── -->
  <div class="chapter-block" id="ch8">
    <div class="chapter-header" data-num="08">
      <div>
        <div class="chapter-num">Chapter 8</div>
        <div class="chapter-title">The Digital Self</div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="section">
      <button class="section-toggle open" onclick="toggleSection(this)">
        <h3><span class="section-icon icon-blue">💻</span>8.1 — Identity in the Digital Age</h3>
        <span class="chevron">▾</span>
      </button>
      <div class="section-body open">
        <h4>The Digital Self</h4>
        <div class="callout callout-def">
          <div class="callout-label">Definition</div>
          <p>The <strong>digital self</strong> is the version of oneself constructed and presented in digital/online spaces — through social media profiles, avatars, usernames, and online behavior.</p>
        </div>

        <h4>Key Concepts</h4>
        <ul class="styled-list">
          <li><span class="term">Online identity</span> — curated presentation of self in digital environments</li>
          <li><span class="term">Digital footprint</span> — trail of data left by online activity</li>
          <li><span class="term">Filter bubble</span> — algorithms showing only content reinforcing existing beliefs, narrowing self-perspective</li>
          <li><span class="term">Cyber self-disclosure</span> — sharing personal information online (often more than offline)</li>
          <li><span class="term">Trolling and cyberbullying</span> — threats to digital self and self-esteem</li>
        </ul>

        <h4>Sherry Turkle — "Alone Together"</h4>
        <p>Turkle observed that technology creates a paradox: we are hyperconnected online but increasingly isolated in real life. The digital self can become a replacement for, rather than an extension of, the authentic self.</p>

        <h4>Digital Well-being</h4>
        <ul class="styled-list">
          <li>Healthy digital habits: mindful social media use, digital detox, online-offline balance</li>
          <li>Critical evaluation of online content — media literacy</li>
          <li>Privacy awareness — protecting digital identity</li>
          <li>Responsible digital citizenship — ethical online behavior</li>
        </ul>

        <h4>The Philippines & Social Media</h4>
        <p>Filipinos are among the world's most active social media users. This creates both opportunities (community, expression, activism) and risks (misinformation, cyberbullying, data privacy).</p>

        <div class="takeaways">
          <div class="takeaways-label">Key Takeaways — Section 8.1</div>
          <ul>
            <li>The digital self is a curated, constructed online identity</li>
            <li>Social media amplifies Cooley's looking glass self and Goffman's impression management</li>
            <li>Digital technology creates the paradox of being "alone together"</li>
            <li>Digital literacy and ethical online behavior are essential for healthy selfhood</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

