    <div class="section">
      <button class="section-toggle open" onclick="toggleSection(this)">
        <h3><span class="section-icon icon-ethics">⚖️</span>E1.1 — What is Ethics?</h3>
        <span class="chevron">▾</span>
      </button>
      <div class="section-body open">
        <div class="callout callout-def">
          <div class="callout-label">Definition</div>
          <p><strong>Ethics</strong> (from Greek <em>ethos</em> = character/custom) is the branch of philosophy that studies morality — what is right and wrong, good and bad, what we ought to do, and what kind of persons we should be.</p>
        </div>

        <h4 class="ethics-h">Three Branches of Ethics</h4>
        <div class="theory-grid">
          <div class="theory-card ethics-card">
            <h5>Metaethics</h5>
            <p>Studies the nature, foundations, and meaning of moral claims. Are moral facts objective? What does "good" mean?</p>
            <span class="thinker" style="color:var(--accent2);">Foundations</span>
          </div>
          <div class="theory-card ethics-card">
            <h5>Normative Ethics</h5>
            <p>Develops theories about what is right and wrong — what norms should guide behavior. Includes virtue ethics, deontology, consequentialism.</p>
            <span class="thinker" style="color:var(--accent2);">Theories</span>
          </div>
          <div class="theory-card ethics-card">
            <h5>Applied Ethics</h5>
            <p>Applies ethical theories to real-world issues: bioethics, environmental ethics, business ethics, digital ethics.</p>
            <span class="thinker" style="color:var(--accent2);">Practice</span>
          </div>
        </div>

        <h4 class="ethics-h">Key Distinctions</h4>
        <table class="compare-table">
          <thead><tr><th>Concept</th><th>Definition</th><th>Example</th></tr></thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr><td>Morality</td><td>The actual standards of right/wrong in a society or culture</td><td>Filipino cultural norms on hospitality</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Ethics</td><td>Philosophical reflection on morality; critical examination of moral standards</td><td>Asking whether bribery is ever justified</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Law</td><td>Codified rules enforced by the state</td><td>Anti-graft law</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Values</td><td>Principles considered important; what we care about</td><td>Honesty, loyalty, justice</td></tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
        <div class="callout callout-warning">
          <div class="callout-label">Important Distinction</div>
          <p>Something can be <em>legal</em> but <em>unethical</em> (e.g., legally permitted tax avoidance that harms public services). Something can be <em>ethical</em> but <em>illegal</em> (e.g., civil disobedience against unjust laws). Law ≠ Ethics.</p>
        </div>

        <h4 class="ethics-h">Moral Relativism vs. Moral Objectivism</h4>
        <ul class="styled-list ethics-list">
          <li><span class="term ethics-t">Moral relativism</span> — moral standards vary by culture/individual; no universal morality. "What's right for you may not be right for me."</li>
          <li><span class="term ethics-t">Moral objectivism</span> — some moral standards are universally true, independent of culture or opinion</li>
          <li><span class="term ethics-t">Cultural relativism</span> — descriptive claim that moral beliefs differ across cultures (this is factually true)</li>
          <li><span class="term ethics-t">Moral absolutism</span> — some actions are always right or wrong regardless of consequences or context</li>
        </ul>

        <div class="callout callout-tip">
          <div class="callout-label">Study Tip</div>
          <p>Distinguish between descriptive relativism (cultures DO differ in values — true) and normative relativism (therefore no moral truth — controversial). Most ethical theories reject normative relativism.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="takeaways ethics-take">
          <div class="takeaways-label">Key Takeaways — E1.1</div>
          <ul>
            <li>Ethics = philosophical study of morality (not just cultural rules)</li>
            <li>Three branches: metaethics, normative ethics, applied ethics</li>
            <li>Law and ethics are distinct; legal ≠ ethical</li>
            <li>Moral relativism vs. objectivism is a foundational debate in metaethics</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- ─── ETHICS 2 & 3: VIRTUE ETHICS ─── -->
  <div class="chapter-block" id="e2">
    <div class="chapter-header ethics-chapter" data-num="E2">
      <div>
        <div class="chapter-num" style="color:var(--accent2);">Chapter E2</div>
        <div class="chapter-title">Overview of Major Moral Theories</div>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="section">
      <button class="section-toggle open" onclick="toggleSection(this)">
        <h3><span class="section-icon icon-ethics">🗂️</span>E2.1 — Mapping the Major Theories</h3>
        <span class="chevron">▾</span>
      </button>
      <div class="section-body open">
        <p>The major normative theories each answer the fundamental question — <em>"What makes an action right?"</em> — differently:</p>
        <table class="compare-table">
          <thead><tr><th>Theory</th><th>Core Question</th><th>Key Focus</th><th>Thinker</th></tr></thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr><td>Virtue Ethics</td><td>What kind of person should I be?</td><td>Character & virtues</td><td>Aristotle</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Deontology</td><td>What is my duty?</td><td>Rules & obligations</td><td>Kant</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Consequentialism/Utilitarianism</td><td>What produces the best outcomes?</td><td>Consequences & welfare</td><td>Bentham, Mill</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Social Contract Theory</td><td>What are the rules of fair cooperation?</td><td>Agreement & justice</td><td>Hobbes, Locke, Rawls</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Care Ethics</td><td>How do I maintain caring relationships?</td><td>Relationships & empathy</td><td>Gilligan, Noddings</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Natural Law Theory</td><td>What is in accord with human nature?</td><td>Human nature & reason</td><td>Aquinas</td></tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
        <div class="callout callout-tip">
          <div class="callout-label">Exam Strategy</div>
          <p>When asked to analyze an ethical dilemma, always apply multiple theories and show how they may arrive at different conclusions. This demonstrates deeper understanding than using only one theory.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
