  </div>

  <!-- ─── ETHICS 3: VIRTUE ETHICS ─── -->
  <div class="chapter-block" id="e3">
    <div class="chapter-header ethics-chapter" data-num="E3">
      <div>
        <div class="chapter-num" style="color:var(--accent2);">Chapter E3</div>
        <div class="chapter-title">Virtue Ethics:<br>Character, Excellence & the Good Life</div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="section">
      <button class="section-toggle open" onclick="toggleSection(this)">
        <h3><span class="section-icon icon-ethics">🏺</span>E3.1 — Aristotelian Virtue Ethics</h3>
        <span class="chevron">▾</span>
      </button>
      <div class="section-body open">
        <div class="philosopher-quote">
          <p>"We are what we repeatedly do. Excellence, then, is not an act but a habit."</p>
          <div class="quote-attr">— Often attributed to Aristotle (paraphrase of Nicomachean Ethics)</div>
        </div>

        <h4 class="ethics-h">Core Concepts</h4>
        <div class="callout callout-def">
          <div class="callout-label">Eudaimonia (Flourishing)</div>
          <p>The highest human good — not mere pleasure or wealth, but <em>flourishing</em>: living and doing well in accordance with one's nature as a rational being. This is the goal of the ethical life.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="callout callout-def">
          <div class="callout-label">Arete (Virtue/Excellence)</div>
          <p>Virtues are excellent traits of character — stable dispositions to act, feel, and think in the right way. They are developed through practice and habit, not innate gifts.</p>
        </div>

        <h4 class="ethics-h">The Doctrine of the Mean</h4>
        <p>Each virtue is the <span class="term ethics-t">golden mean</span> between two vices — one of excess and one of deficiency:</p>
        <table class="compare-table">
          <thead><tr><th>Vice of Deficiency</th><th>Virtue (Mean)</th><th>Vice of Excess</th></tr></thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr><td>Cowardice</td><td><strong>Courage</strong></td><td>Recklessness</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Miserliness</td><td><strong>Generosity</strong></td><td>Prodigality</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Self-deprecation</td><td><strong>Truthfulness</strong></td><td>Boastfulness</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Boorishness</td><td><strong>Wit/Humor</strong></td><td>Buffoonery</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Apathy</td><td><strong>Proper anger</strong></td><td>Irascibility</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Insensibility</td><td><strong>Temperance</strong></td><td>Intemperance</td></tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>

        <h4 class="ethics-h">Cardinal Virtues (Classical)</h4>
        <ul class="styled-list ethics-list">
          <li><strong>Prudence (Phronesis)</strong> — practical wisdom; knowing what to do in particular situations</li>
          <li><strong>Justice (Dikaiosyne)</strong> — giving each person their due; fairness</li>
          <li><strong>Fortitude (Andreia)</strong> — courage; facing danger appropriately</li>
          <li><strong>Temperance (Sophrosyne)</strong> — self-control; moderation of desires</li>
        </ul>

        <h4 class="ethics-h">Theological Virtues (Aquinas)</h4>
        <ul class="styled-list ethics-list">
          <li><strong>Faith</strong> — trust in God's revelation</li>
          <li><strong>Hope</strong> — confident expectation of God's promises</li>
          <li><strong>Charity (Love)</strong> — love of God and neighbor; the greatest virtue</li>
        </ul>

        <h4 class="ethics-h">Modern Virtue Ethics — Alasdair MacIntyre</h4>
        <p>MacIntyre argued that virtues are intelligible only within social <span class="term ethics-t">practices</span> and traditions. The virtues relevant to a Filipino community may differ from those of an ancient Greek polis — but virtues remain essential to the good life.</p>

        <h4 class="ethics-h">Advantages & Criticisms of Virtue Ethics</h4>
        <table class="compare-table">
          <thead><tr><th>Advantages</th><th>Criticisms</th></tr></thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr><td>Emphasizes character, not just acts</td><td>Vague action guidance ("what would a virtuous person do?")</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Captures moral development over time</td><td>Virtues may be culturally relative</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Motivationally rich (aspiration to be good)</td><td>May not resolve conflicts between virtues</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Matches everyday moral psychology</td><td>Who counts as the virtuous person (standard)?</td></tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>

        <div class="takeaways ethics-take">
          <div class="takeaways-label">Key Takeaways — E3.1</div>
          <ul>
            <li>Virtue ethics focuses on character, not just acts: "Be good, and you'll do good"</li>
            <li>Eudaimonia (flourishing) is the ultimate goal of the virtuous life</li>
            <li>The doctrine of the mean: virtue is between excess and deficiency</li>
            <li>Virtues are habits — developed through repeated practice</li>
            <li>Phronesis (practical wisdom) is the master virtue</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="pq-block">
      <div class="pq-question" onclick="toggleAnswer(this)">
        <span class="pq-num ethics-num">Q5</span>
        <span>Using Aristotle's doctrine of the mean, analyze the virtue of courage in the context of a Filipino whistleblower exposing government corruption.</span>
      </div>
      <div class="pq-answer">
        <div class="pq-answer-label">Model Answer</div>
        Aristotle defines courage as the mean between cowardice (deficiency — refusing to act from fear) and recklessness (excess — acting without prudence). A Filipino whistleblower faces real dangers (threats, legal harassment, social ostracism). <em>Cowardice</em> would be staying silent when one has clear knowledge of wrongdoing, purely to protect oneself. <em>Recklessness</em> would be exposing information without any preparation, risking not only oneself but others unnecessarily. True <em>courage</em> involves carefully weighing the risks, preparing adequately (legal protection, documentation), and choosing to act for justice despite fear — not without it. Phronesis (practical wisdom) guides the courageous person to expose wrongdoing in the most effective and safest way possible.
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- ─── ETHICS 4: DEONTOLOGY ─── -->
  <div class="chapter-block" id="e4">
    <div class="chapter-header ethics-chapter" data-num="E4">
      <div>
        <div class="chapter-num" style="color:var(--accent2);">Chapter E4</div>
        <div class="chapter-title">Deontological Ethics:<br>Duty, Rights & the Categorical Imperative</div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="section">
      <button class="section-toggle open" onclick="toggleSection(this)">
        <h3><span class="section-icon icon-ethics">📋</span>E4.1 — Kant's Deontological Ethics</h3>
        <span class="chevron">▾</span>
      </button>
      <div class="section-body open">
        <div class="philosopher-quote">
          <p>"Act only according to that maxim by which you can at the same time will that it should become a universal law."</p>
          <div class="quote-attr">— Immanuel Kant, Groundwork of the Metaphysics of Morals (1785)</div>
        </div>

        <h4 class="ethics-h">Core Principle of Deontology</h4>
        <div class="callout callout-def">
          <div class="callout-label">Deontology</div>
          <p>From Greek <em>deon</em> = duty. The rightness or wrongness of an action is determined by whether it conforms to moral rules/duties — <em>not</em> by its consequences. Some actions are intrinsically right or wrong.</p>
        </div>

        <h4 class="ethics-h">The Categorical Imperative</h4>
        <p>Kant's supreme principle of morality — the <span class="term ethics-t">Categorical Imperative (CI)</span> — commands unconditionally (unlike hypothetical imperatives which are conditional on desires).</p>

        <p><strong>Three Formulations of the CI:</strong></p>

        <div class="callout callout-def">
          <div class="callout-label">Formula 1 — Universal Law</div>
          <p>"Act only according to that maxim whereby you can at the same time will that it should become a universal law."<br><br>Test: Could your action's principle be universalized without contradiction?</p>
        </div>
        <div class="callout callout-example">
          <div class="callout-label">Application</div>
          <p>Lying: Maxim = "I will lie when convenient." Universalized: If everyone lied, the practice of truth-telling collapses — the maxim self-destructs. Therefore, lying is impermissible.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="callout callout-def">
          <div class="callout-label">Formula 2 — Humanity Formula</div>
          <p>"Act so that you treat humanity, whether in your own person or that of another, always as an end and never as a means only."<br><br>Persons have inherent dignity (Würde) — they must never be merely used.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="callout callout-example">
          <div class="callout-label">Application</div>
          <p>Manipulation, slavery, and exploitation violate the humanity formula — they treat persons as mere tools for others' ends.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="callout callout-def">
          <div class="callout-label">Formula 3 — Kingdom of Ends</div>
          <p>"Act according to maxims of a universally legislating member of a merely possible kingdom of ends."<br><br>Imagine a moral community where all rational beings are both lawmakers and subjects of the moral law.</p>
        </div>

        <h4 class="ethics-h">Key Kantian Concepts</h4>
        <ul class="styled-list ethics-list">
          <li><span class="term ethics-t">Good will</span> — the only unconditionally good thing; a will that acts from duty</li>
          <li><span class="term ethics-t">Acting from duty vs. in accord with duty</span> — helping others because it's right (from duty) vs. because you feel like it (in accord with duty, but not moral worth)</li>
          <li><span class="term ethics-t">Perfect duties</span> — absolute duties that admit no exceptions (e.g., do not murder, do not lie)</li>
          <li><span class="term ethics-t">Imperfect duties</span> — duties that allow latitude in how to fulfill them (e.g., duty to help others, duty to develop talents)</li>
          <li><span class="term ethics-t">Human dignity (Würde)</span> — rational beings have absolute worth; not a price (replaceable) but dignity (irreplaceable)</li>
        </ul>

        <h4 class="ethics-h">Rights-Based Deontology</h4>
        <p>Rights-based theories (John Locke, Robert Nozick) hold that persons have natural rights — to life, liberty, property — that must not be violated even for good consequences.</p>
        <div class="callout callout-example">
          <div class="callout-label">Example</div>
          <p>Even if killing one person would save five, deontologists argue you cannot murder an innocent person — that violates their right to life absolutely. Consequences don't override rights.</p>
        </div>

        <h4 class="ethics-h">W.D. Ross — Prima Facie Duties</h4>
        <p>Ross offered a more flexible deontology. We have multiple <span class="term ethics-t">prima facie duties</span> — duties that are binding unless overridden by a stronger duty:</p>
        <ul class="styled-list ethics-list">
          <li>Fidelity — keeping promises</li>
          <li>Reparation — making amends for wrongs done</li>
          <li>Gratitude — reciprocating benefits received</li>
          <li>Non-maleficence — do no harm</li>
          <li>Beneficence — do good to others</li>
          <li>Justice — distribute goods fairly</li>
          <li>Self-improvement — develop your own talents</li>
        </ul>

        <h4 class="ethics-h">Advantages & Criticisms</h4>
        <table class="compare-table">
          <thead><tr><th>Advantages</th><th>Criticisms</th></tr></thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr><td>Protects individual rights absolutely</td><td>Ignores consequences (can lead to absurd results)</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Clear moral rules; predictable</td><td>Rigid: what if duties conflict?</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Respects human dignity</td><td>Kant: never lie — even to murderer asking where victim hides?</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Treats persons as ends, not means</td><td>Difficulty determining what counts as a "universal law"</td></tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>

        <div class="takeaways ethics-take">
          <div class="takeaways-label">Key Takeaways — E4.1</div>
          <ul>
            <li>Deontology: rightness depends on duty/rules, not consequences</li>
            <li>CI Formula 1: universalizability test — could everyone do this?</li>
            <li>CI Formula 2: never treat persons merely as means — respect dignity</li>
            <li>Good will: the only unconditionally good thing</li>
            <li>Ross's prima facie duties soften Kant's rigidity</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="pq-block">
      <div class="pq-question" onclick="toggleAnswer(this)">
        <span class="pq-num ethics-num">Q6</span>
        <span>A politician uses a vulnerable community's votes by promising false infrastructure projects. Analyze this using Kant's Categorical Imperative (Formula 2).</span>
      </div>
      <div class="pq-answer">
        <div class="pq-answer-label">Model Answer</div>
        Kant's Formula 2 commands: treat humanity always as an end in itself, never merely as a means. The politician treats voters as <em>means</em> to achieve the end of political power — using false promises to manipulate them without their rational consent. The voters are deceived, not respected as rational agents capable of making informed decisions. Their dignity (Würde) is violated. Kant would condemn this absolutely, regardless of whether the politician later does some good in office. The act of manipulation is intrinsically wrong — it reduces persons to instruments.
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- ─── ETHICS 5: CONSEQUENTIALISM ─── -->
  <div class="chapter-block" id="e5">
    <div class="chapter-header ethics-chapter" data-num="E5">
      <div>
        <div class="chapter-num" style="color:var(--accent2);">Chapter E5</div>
        <div class="chapter-title">Consequentialism & Utilitarianism</div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="section">
      <button class="section-toggle open" onclick="toggleSection(this)">
        <h3><span class="section-icon icon-ethics">📊</span>E5.1 — The Greatest Good for the Greatest Number</h3>
        <span class="chevron">▾</span>
      </button>
      <div class="section-body open">
        <div class="callout callout-def">
          <div class="callout-label">Consequentialism</div>
          <p>The rightness of an action is determined solely by its consequences — specifically, whether it maximizes good outcomes (welfare, happiness, well-being) for those affected.</p>
        </div>

        <h4 class="ethics-h">Jeremy Bentham — Act Utilitarianism</h4>
        <p>Bentham founded utilitarianism. His principle of utility: produce the greatest happiness for the greatest number. He proposed the <span class="term ethics-t">hedonic calculus</span> to measure pleasure and pain:</p>
        <div class="formula">
Factors of the Hedonic Calculus:
1. Intensity — how strong is the pleasure/pain?
2. Duration — how long does it last?
3. Certainty — how likely is it?
4. Propinquity — how soon will it occur?
5. Fecundity — will it produce more pleasure?
6. Purity — will it produce pain as well?
7. Extent — how many people are affected?
        </div>
        <p>Sum up pleasures and pains across all affected → if net pleasure > net pain → action is right.</p>

        <h4 class="ethics-h">John Stuart Mill — Refined Utilitarianism</h4>
        <p>Mill modified Bentham by arguing pleasures differ in quality, not just quantity:</p>
        <div class="callout callout-def">
          <div class="callout-label">Higher vs. Lower Pleasures</div>
          <p>"It is better to be Socrates dissatisfied than a fool satisfied." Higher pleasures (intellectual, moral, aesthetic) are qualitatively superior to lower pleasures (purely physical).</p>
        </div>
        <p>Mill also defended <span class="term ethics-t">rule utilitarianism</span>: follow rules that generally maximize utility (e.g., "do not lie") rather than calculating consequences act by act.</p>

        <h4 class="ethics-h">Act vs. Rule Utilitarianism</h4>
        <table class="compare-table">
          <thead><tr><th></th><th>Act Utilitarianism</th><th>Rule Utilitarianism</th></tr></thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr><td>Principle</td><td>Each act judged by consequences</td><td>Follow rules that maximize utility</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Flexibility</td><td>High — exceptions always possible</td><td>Lower — rules provide stability</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Problem</td><td>Can justify horrific acts</td><td>Rules can conflict; still outcome-based</td></tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>

        <h4 class="ethics-h">Peter Singer — Effective Altruism & Global Obligations</h4>
        <p>Singer extends utilitarian logic globally: if we can prevent suffering without sacrificing anything of comparable moral importance, we are morally obligated to do so. This challenges comfortable middle-class lifestyles in wealthy nations.</p>
        <div class="callout callout-example">
          <div class="callout-label">Application to the Philippines</div>
          <p>A utilitarian analysis of the Pantawid Pamilyang Pilipino Program (4Ps) would assess its net welfare impact: Does it increase happiness/well-being for the greatest number? Evidence-based policy is inherently utilitarian in approach.</p>
        </div>

        <h4 class="ethics-h">Classic Objections to Utilitarianism</h4>
        <ul class="styled-list ethics-list">
          <li><strong>The justice objection</strong>: utilitarianism can justify punishing an innocent person if it prevents greater harm (scapegoating)</li>
          <li><strong>The integrity objection</strong> (Bernard Williams): it alienates us from our own deepest commitments and personal projects</li>
          <li><strong>The demandingness objection</strong>: always maximizing utility is impossibly demanding — you should always give up luxuries for the poor</li>
          <li><strong>The rights objection</strong>: individual rights can be sacrificed for aggregate welfare</li>
        </ul>

        <div class="takeaways ethics-take">
          <div class="takeaways-label">Key Takeaways — E5.1</div>
          <ul>
            <li>Consequentialism: rightness determined by outcomes, not rules or character</li>
            <li>Bentham: greatest happiness principle + hedonic calculus</li>
            <li>Mill: quality of pleasures matters; higher pleasures are superior</li>
            <li>Act vs. rule utilitarianism — different ways of applying the principle</li>
            <li>Main objections: justice, integrity, demandingness, rights violations</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="pq-block">
      <div class="pq-question" onclick="toggleAnswer(this)">
        <span class="pq-num ethics-num">Q7</span>
        <span>The government must decide whether to demolish an informal settlers community to build a hospital that will serve hundreds of thousands. Analyze using both utilitarianism and Kantian ethics.</span>
      </div>
      <div class="pq-answer">
        <div class="pq-answer-label">Model Answer</div>
        <strong>Utilitarian view:</strong> A utilitarian would calculate net welfare — if the hospital saves thousands of lives and the displaced residents are adequately relocated and compensated, the net utility gained (thousands helped) may outweigh the harm (hundreds displaced). A utilitarian would support the demolition IF proper relocation is provided. However, if residents are left worse off, the calculus changes.<br><br>
        <strong>Kantian view:</strong> Kant's humanity formula prohibits treating the settlers merely as means. Demolishing their homes — even for a noble end (hospital) — without their genuine consent treats them as instruments for others' welfare, violating their dignity. Kant would require genuine consent and participation in the decision. A just solution would involve the community in planning, not simply override their rights for aggregate benefit.
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- ─── ETHICS 6: SOCIAL CONTRACT ─── -->
  <div class="chapter-block" id="e6">
    <div class="chapter-header ethics-chapter" data-num="E6">
      <div>
        <div class="chapter-num" style="color:var(--accent2);">Chapter E6</div>
        <div class="chapter-title">Social Contract Theory &<br>Justice</div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="section">
      <button class="section-toggle open" onclick="toggleSection(this)">
        <h3><span class="section-icon icon-ethics">🤝</span>E6.1 — The Social Contract Tradition</h3>
        <span class="chevron">▾</span>
      </button>
      <div class="section-body open">
        <div class="callout callout-def">
          <div class="callout-label">Social Contract</div>
          <p>The idea that morality and political authority derive from an agreement (actual or hypothetical) among individuals. The state is justified by the consent of the governed, and morality consists in principles rational people would agree to.</p>
        </div>

        <h4 class="ethics-h">Thomas Hobbes — Leviathan (1651)</h4>
        <p>Without government, life in the "state of nature" is <em>"solitary, poor, nasty, brutish, and short."</em> Rational self-interest leads people to contract with a sovereign power for security, surrendering freedom in exchange for protection.</p>
        <ul class="styled-list ethics-list">
          <li>Hobbes' morality: rules that rational, self-interested people would agree to for mutual benefit</li>
          <li>The social contract is essentially <em>self-interested cooperation</em></li>
        </ul>

        <h4 class="ethics-h">John Locke — Natural Rights & Limited Government</h4>
        <p>Locke argued humans have natural rights to <strong>life, liberty, and property</strong> prior to government. The social contract creates government to protect these rights — and the people can revolt if government violates them.</p>
        <p>Locke's ideas directly influenced the American Declaration of Independence and modern constitutionalism — including the Philippine Constitution.</p>

        <h4 class="ethics-h">Jean-Jacques Rousseau — The General Will</h4>
        <p>Rousseau distinguished between the <em>will of all</em> (sum of individual interests) and the <span class="term ethics-t">general will</span> (the common good). True freedom is obeying the laws you give yourself as a member of the political community.</p>

        <h4 class="ethics-h">John Rawls — Justice as Fairness</h4>
        <div class="callout callout-def">
          <div class="callout-label">The Veil of Ignorance</div>
          <p>Rawls asks: what principles of justice would rational people choose if they didn't know their position in society (their class, race, gender, abilities)? Behind this "veil of ignorance," rational people would choose fair principles.</p>
        </div>
        <p>Rawls' Two Principles of Justice:</p>
        <ul class="styled-list ethics-list">
          <li><span class="term ethics-t">Equal basic liberties principle</span>: Each person has the same right to the most extensive system of equal basic liberties compatible with similar liberty for all</li>
          <li><span class="term ethics-t">Difference principle</span>: Social and economic inequalities are permissible only if they benefit the least advantaged members of society</li>
        </ul>
        <div class="callout callout-example">
          <div class="callout-label">Application</div>
          <p>Rawls' difference principle supports progressive taxation and social safety nets — economic inequalities (e.g., some earning more than others) are just only if they improve the condition of the poorest. This is a major argument for welfare state policies.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="takeaways ethics-take">
          <div class="takeaways-label">Key Takeaways — E6.1</div>
          <ul>
            <li>Social contract: morality and government derive from rational agreement</li>
            <li>Hobbes: contract from self-interest (avoid violent state of nature)</li>
            <li>Locke: natural rights; government protects life, liberty, property</li>
            <li>Rawls: justice as fairness; veil of ignorance; difference principle</li>
            <li>Rawls' theory supports welfare and redistribution for the least advantaged</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

