        <div class="callout callout-def">
          <div class="callout-label">Bioethics</div>
          <p>The ethical study of issues in biology, medicine, and healthcare — including decisions about life, death, treatment, research, and the human body.</p>
        </div>

        <h4 class="ethics-h">Beauchamp & Childress — Four Principles (Principlism)</h4>
        <div class="theory-grid">
          <div class="theory-card ethics-card">
            <h5>Autonomy</h5>
            <p>Respect patients' right to make informed decisions about their own healthcare.</p>
            <span class="thinker" style="color:var(--accent2);">Beauchamp & Childress</span>
          </div>
          <div class="theory-card ethics-card">
            <h5>Beneficence</h5>
            <p>Act in the patient's best interest — actively promote their welfare.</p>
            <span class="thinker" style="color:var(--accent2);">Beauchamp & Childress</span>
          </div>
          <div class="theory-card ethics-card">
            <h5>Non-Maleficence</h5>
            <p>"First, do no harm" (primum non nocere). Avoid actions that cause harm.</p>
            <span class="thinker" style="color:var(--accent2);">Beauchamp & Childress</span>
          </div>
          <div class="theory-card ethics-card">
            <h5>Justice</h5>
            <p>Fair distribution of healthcare resources; equal treatment regardless of background.</p>
            <span class="thinker" style="color:var(--accent2);">Beauchamp & Childress</span>
          </div>
        </div>

        <h4 class="ethics-h">Major Bioethical Issues</h4>

        <h5>Abortion</h5>
        <p>When does morally significant life begin? Key positions:</p>
        <ul class="styled-list ethics-list">
          <li><strong>Pro-life</strong>: Personhood begins at fertilization; abortion is always wrong</li>
          <li><strong>Pro-choice</strong>: Bodily autonomy of the woman is primary; personhood develops gradually</li>
          <li><strong>Moderate views</strong>: Abortion permissible early in pregnancy or in certain circumstances</li>
        </ul>
        <p>In the Philippines: Abortion is illegal under the Revised Penal Code. The Reproductive Health Law (2012) guarantees access to contraception but not abortion. This is a major church-state tension.</p>

        <h5>Euthanasia and Assisted Dying</h5>
        <table class="compare-table">
          <thead><tr><th>Type</th><th>Definition</th></tr></thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr><td>Voluntary active euthanasia</td><td>Medical professional actively causes death at patient's request</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Passive euthanasia</td><td>Withdrawal of life-sustaining treatment</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Physician-assisted suicide</td><td>Doctor provides means; patient self-administers</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Involuntary euthanasia</td><td>Ending life without patient's consent — generally considered murder</td></tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
        <p>Philippines: Euthanasia is illegal. The Catholic Church strongly opposes it. Key ethical arguments: autonomy vs. sanctity of life.</p>

        <h5>Genetic Engineering & CRISPR</h5>
        <ul class="styled-list ethics-list">
          <li>Gene editing for disease prevention vs. "designer babies"</li>
          <li>Eugenics concerns — historical abuses (Nazi Germany)</li>
          <li>Somatic vs. germline editing — germline changes are heritable</li>
          <li>Access justice: who benefits from genetic technology?</li>
        </ul>

        <h5>Organ Transplantation & Allocation</h5>
        <ul class="styled-list ethics-list">
          <li>Who gets scarce organs? Utilitarian (maximize lives saved) vs. fairness (equality, first-come-first-served)</li>
          <li>Selling organs: commodification of the body — violates human dignity?</li>
          <li>Living donors vs. cadaveric donation — opt-in vs. opt-out policies</li>
        </ul>

        <div class="takeaways ethics-take">
          <div class="takeaways-label">Key Takeaways — E8.1</div>
          <ul>
            <li>Four bioethical principles: autonomy, beneficence, non-maleficence, justice</li>
            <li>Abortion: personhood question central; illegal in the Philippines</li>
            <li>Euthanasia: autonomy vs. sanctity of life; illegal in Philippines</li>
            <li>Genetic engineering raises concerns about eugenics and justice</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

