    <div class="pq-block">
      <div class="pq-question" onclick="toggleAnswer(this)">
        <span class="pq-num ethics-num">Q8</span>
        <span>A local government official accepts a gift from a contractor who later wins a public works bid. Analyze using virtue ethics, deontology, and consequentialism.</span>
      </div>
      <div class="pq-answer">
        <div class="pq-answer-label">Model Answer</div>
        <strong>Virtue Ethics:</strong> The official lacks the virtues of justice (not giving each their due), integrity, and practical wisdom (phronesis). A virtuous person would not place themselves in a position of conflict of interest. The habit of accepting gifts corrupts character over time.<br><br>
        <strong>Deontology (Kant):</strong> CI Formula 1 — universalized, if all officials accepted gifts from contractors, the public bidding system would collapse (contradiction → impermissible). Formula 2 — using public office for private benefit treats citizens as means (their taxes exploited for the official's gain).<br><br>
        <strong>Utilitarianism:</strong> The aggregate harm — reduced quality of public works, public funds wasted, erosion of trust in government, long-term institutional damage — far outweighs the benefit to the official and contractor. A utilitarian would condemn this as producing net negative outcomes.
      </div>
