    <div class="pq-block">
      <div class="pq-question" onclick="toggleAnswer(this)">
        <span class="pq-num">Q9</span>
        <span>How does Sartre's existentialism challenge the idea that Filipinos are naturally hospitable or family-oriented?</span>
      </div>
      <div class="pq-answer">
        <div class="pq-answer-label">Model Answer</div>
        Sartre's "existence precedes essence" means there is no pre-given Filipino nature — hospitality and family orientation are not biological facts but values chosen, practiced, and reinforced through culture and individual choices. Sartre would say these traits are part of a social "spirit of seriousness" — treating contingent values as if they were fixed essences (a form of "bad faith"). A Filipino who is genuinely hospitable chooses that value authentically; one who is hospitable only because "that's what Filipinos do" acts in bad faith. Sartre's view is liberating: Filipinos can freely embrace, modify, or reject cultural values — they are not determined by them.
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="pq-block">
      <div class="pq-question" onclick="toggleAnswer(this)">
        <span class="pq-num">Q10</span>
        <span>Compare Maslow's self-actualization with Aristotle's eudaimonia. How are they similar and different?</span>
      </div>
      <div class="pq-answer">
        <div class="pq-answer-label">Model Answer</div>
        <strong>Similarities:</strong> Both Maslow and Aristotle see human beings as having a telos — a natural endpoint or fulfillment. Both emphasize that the highest human good involves realizing one's fullest potential. Both value creativity, authentic living, and a life of active engagement with one's capacities.<br><br>
        <strong>Differences:</strong> Aristotle's eudaimonia is fundamentally social — it requires living virtuously within a community, exercising reason, and fulfilling one's role as a citizen. Maslow's self-actualization is more individualistic — the pinnacle of personal psychological fulfillment. Aristotle's virtue-based path is prescriptive (you must develop specific virtues); Maslow's hierarchy is descriptive of motivation. Eudaimonia is about excellent activity; self-actualization is about reaching one's unique potential.
      </div>
    </div>

    <div style="font-size:.75rem;text-transform:uppercase;letter-spacing:2px;color:var(--accent2);font-weight:700;margin:24px 0 12px;">Ethics</div>

    <div class="pq-block">
      <div class="pq-question" onclick="toggleAnswer(this)">
        <span class="pq-num ethics-num">Q11</span>
        <span>Is lying ever morally permissible? Compare Kant and Mill on this issue.</span>
      </div>
      <div class="pq-answer">
        <div class="pq-answer-label">Model Answer</div>
        <strong>Kant:</strong> Lying is never permissible. The maxim "I will lie when convenient" cannot be universalized — if everyone lied, the institution of truth-telling would collapse (contradiction in concept). Moreover, lying violates the humanity formula: it manipulates the listener, denying their rational autonomy. Even to a murderer asking where your friend hides, Kant says you must tell the truth.<br><br>
        <strong>Mill:</strong> A utilitarian can permit lying when it produces better consequences. Lying to the murderer to save a friend's life clearly maximizes welfare — the utility of preventing death outweighs the harm of deception. Rule utilitarians might still hesitate: a rule permitting lying in "good" situations is hard to apply consistently. But most consequentialists would affirm: yes, lying is permissible — even required — when it prevents greater harm.<br><br>
        <strong>Verdict:</strong> This debate illustrates the core deontology-consequentialism divide. Most ordinary moral intuitions support the utilitarian position (lying to save a life is right), but Kant's absolutism highlights the danger of allowing exceptions that erode respect for persons generally.
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="pq-block">
      <div class="pq-question" onclick="toggleAnswer(this)">
        <span class="pq-num ethics-num">Q12</span>
        <span>What is the "veil of ignorance" and how does Rawls use it to argue for redistributive justice?</span>
      </div>
      <div class="pq-answer">
        <div class="pq-answer-label">Model Answer</div>
        The veil of ignorance is a hypothetical thought experiment by Rawls: imagine designing society's basic institutions without knowing your position in it — your class, gender, race, talents, or conception of the good. This "original position" ensures impartiality.<br><br>
        Behind the veil, rational people cannot gamble on being born wealthy or talented. They would therefore choose principles that protect the worst-off position, since they might be the least advantaged. This leads to Rawls' difference principle: social and economic inequalities are just only if they benefit the least advantaged members. This supports progressive taxation, universal healthcare, and social safety nets — not from charity but from justice: these are the rules rational people would choose if they didn't know their place in the lottery of birth.
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

